                            <comment id="16777916" author="garydgregory" created="Tue, 26 Feb 2019 13:39:26 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=drmlipp&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;drmlipp&quot;&gt;drmlipp&lt;/a&gt;,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The log4j-1.2-api module was designed to provide compatibility to 1.2 call sites backed by our log4j-core implementation, as opposed to an SPI implemented by log4j-core. If you can provide a PR to make it work like an SPI, I think that would be neat. I wonder what others think.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Gary&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16778036" author="ralph.goers@dslextreme.com" created="Tue, 26 Feb 2019 15:15:58 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Actually, I would have preferred if the log4j-1.2-api could have just used the log4j api. When I wrote it I remember running up against things the log4j 1.2 api exposed that required the internals of log4j 2, such as the Category class trying to access its parent. With the addition of the stuff in the config package - an attempt to help migration from 1.2 configurations to 2.x config files - it got even worse.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That said, I would be fine moving the config stuff to another module if a way can be found to have log4j-1.2-api rely only on the log4j api.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16778104" author="drmlipp" created="Tue, 26 Feb 2019 15:54:47 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;It depends on what you sacrifice, I suppose. SLF4 seems to have succeeded in providing a (maybe) 95% solution &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.slf4j.org/legacy.html#log4j-over-slf4j&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;with replacement classes&lt;/a&gt;. This could be a way to go for a log4j12-to-log4j that avoids dependencies beyond the SPI. But probably 95% is not enough for a module provided by the log4j authors themselves.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For me, it would have been a shortcut. I&apos;m in the process of writing some &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/mnlipp/de.mnl.osgi#logging-bridgesfacades&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;xxx2osgi modules&lt;/a&gt; and as I have already finished the log4j2osgi module, I had hoped to simply combine it with the log4j-1.2-api for the &quot;legacy&quot; cases. Of course, a log4j122osgi (I&apos;l have to think about this name) will be a bit more efficient anyway.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16892786" author="abpicoli_br" created="Thu, 25 Jul 2019 14:09:51 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;In my practical case I was really blindly believing that log4j 1.2 compatibility would rely only on log4j API, not core. After all this &lt;b&gt;is&lt;/b&gt; what SLF4J does. And it is supposed that log4j 2 API would be a better replacement for slf4j, right?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve created a new SPI and tried to use it with the log4j 1.2 compatibility layer... Boom! My whole solution idea got down the drain... I&apos;m author of the duplicated 2264 issue...&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16892795" author="abpicoli_br" created="Thu, 25 Jul 2019 14:17:39 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Ow man :/ ... all right... I&apos;ve just thought of a workaround ... use log4j1.2 to slf4j bridge, slf4j api, and then use slf4j to log4j2 bridge to my use case...&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
